Gamma         0.00000000E+00  0.00000000E+00  0.00000000E+00
Delta         2.50000000E-01  0.00000000E+00  0.00000000E+00
X             5.00000000E-01  0.00000000E+00  0.00000000E+00
Sigma         2.50000000E-01  2.50000000E-01  0.00000000E+00
Z             5.00000000E-01  2.50000000E-01  0.00000000E+00
M             5.00000000E-01  5.00000000E-01  0.00000000E+00
Lambda        2.50000000E-01  2.50000000E-01  2.50000000E-01
S             5.00000000E-01  2.50000000E-01  2.50000000E-01
T             5.00000000E-01  5.00000000E-01  2.50000000E-01
R             5.00000000E-01  5.00000000E-01  5.00000000E-01

In this mail I shall roughly describe how to determine
short-range interaction parameters j1-j7 and kappa2.

[1]
Erratum of TABLE I in W. Zhong and D. Vanderbilt and Karin
M. Rabe: Phys. Rev. B vol.52 pp.6301-6312 (1995):

incorrect: k2+j2-2j4+4j6
correct:   k2-j2-2j4+4j6

Karin said that it is only typo and listed parameters are correct.


[2]
(a)-(g) in attached SANY0662.JPG are corresponding k-points
and modes in the dispersion diagram of "optical phonon" to
those of FIG.2 and TABLE I in the paper. SANY0662.JPG is
a dispersion diagram of
   (long-range interaction) + (j2-only short-range interaction),
where kappa2, j1, j3, j4, j5, j6, j7 are set to zero. Compare
it to attached sc.energy.without-correction.jpg, the long-range-
interaction-only plot. (Sorry, units of vertical axes are not
same.) Such dispersion plots will help your understanding.


[3]
I have calculated force matrices (DDB files) of the k-points for
PbTiO3 with ABINIT, for example. You can download them with SUBVERSION as
$ svn checkout http://loto.svn.sourceforge.net/svnroot/loto/feram/trunk/src/10-example-PbTiO3-DDB2short
Here, we use force matrices. Not mass-weighted dynamical matrices.


[4]
Calculate eigenvalues and eigenvectors of the force matrices.
You can use attached diagonalize15x15.F.
Select seven eigenvalues corresponding to the (a)-(g), according
to the eigenvectors. There is a difficulty in this selection,
because we employ coarse-graining and reduce the number of
freedom from 15 to 6 per unit cell. There may be no 1-to-1
correspondence.


[5]
>From the seven eigenvalues and TABLE I, you can determine
kappa2 and j1-j7.


(a) -4.188790 = 4*pi/3
(b)  9.687445
(c) -4.843723
(d) -5.353578
(e)  2.676787
(f)  0.0
(g)  5.864529


[examples]
